 of verse, the correspondence of John Donne, the self-fashioning of English gentlemen after the classical Romans of their class and the government's paranoiac spying on its own citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexManuscriptsxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literaturexManuscriptsxHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literaturexManuscriptsxHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literaturexManuscriptsyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexManuscriptsyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aRenaissancexEnglandxEngland. 0aRenaissancezEngland. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aDonne.  aLetters.  aManuscript.  aParkhurst.  aRenaissance.  aVerse.1 aRedford, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedford, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610450240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526104502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526104502/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles